{"title_page": "K\u00e1roly Peyer", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name = K\u00e1roly Peyer\n| image =Peyer K\u00e1roly.png\n| order = [[Minister of the Interior of Hungary]]\n| term_start = 1 August 1919\n| term_end = 7 August 1919\n| president =\n| predecessor = [[Jen\u0151 Landler]] and [[B\u00e9la V\u00e1g\u00f3]]\n| successor = [[Adolf Samassa]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1881|05|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[V\u00e1rosl\u0151d]], [[Hungary]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1956|10|25|1881|05|09|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[New York City]], [[United States]]\n| profession = [[politician]]\n| party = [[Hungarian Social Democratic Party|MSZDP]]\n|}}\n{{eastern name order|Peyer K\u00e1roly}}\n'''K\u00e1roly Peyer''' (9 May 1881 \u2013 25 October 1956) was a [[Hungary|Hungarian]] politician who served as [[Government of Hungary|Interior Minister]] for six days after the end of the [[Hungarian Soviet Republic]] in 1919. He was later Minister of Works in the cabinets of [[Istv\u00e1n Friedrich]] and [[K\u00e1roly Husz\u00e1r]]. He took part in the consolidation policy of [[Istv\u00e1n Bethlen]] in 1921: as the leader of the main opposition party (the [[Hungarian Social Democratic Party]]) he compromised with the Prime Minister (the Bethlen-Peyer Pact). Peyer was called \"betrayer of the left-wing\" by the [[communist]]s.\n\nIn 1947 Peyer was excluded from his party, so he joined to the Hungarian Radical Party, which organised against communist rule. Soon Peyer emigrated to the [[United States]]. The next year the People's Tribunal sentenced him to 8 years.\n\nPeyer died of a heart attack on 25 October 1956, while listening to the news of the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]], which broke out two days earlier.\n\n==References==\n* [http://mek.oszk.hu/00300/00355/html/index.html Magyar \u00c9letrajzi Lexikon]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Interior Minister of Hungary|Minister of the Interior]]|before=[[Jen\u0151 Landler]] and [[B\u00e9la V\u00e1g\u00f3]]|after=[[Adolf Samassa]]|years=1919}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{HungarianInteriorMinisters}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peyer, Karoly}}\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1956 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Veszpr\u00e9m County]]\n[[Category:Hungarian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Social Democratic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Radical Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Interior Ministers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Diet of Hungary]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of Hungary (1945\u20131947)]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of Hungary (1947\u20131949)]]\n[[Category:Hungarian emigrants to the United States]]\n\n\n{{Hungary-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name = K\u00e1roly Peyer\n| image =Peyer K\u00e1roly.png\n| order = [[Minister of the Interior of Hungary]]\n| term_start = 1 August 1919\n| term_end = 7 August 1919\n| president =\n| predecessor = [[Jen\u0151 Landler]] and [[B\u00e9la V\u00e1g\u00f3]]\n| successor = [[Adolf Samassa]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1881|05|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[V\u00e1rosl\u0151d]], [[Hungary]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1956|10|25|1881|05|09|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[New York City]], [[United States]]\n| profession = [[politician]]\n| party = [[Hungarian Social Democratic Party|MSZDP]]\n|}}\n{{eastern name order|Peyer K\u00e1roly}}\n'''K\u00e1roly Peyer''' (9 May 1881 \u2013 25 October 1956) was a [[Hungary|Hungarian]] politician who served as [[Government of Hungary|Interior Minister]] for six days after the end of the [[Hungarian Soviet Republic]] in 1919. He was later Minister of Works in the cabinets of [[Istv\u00e1n Friedrich]] and [[K\u00e1roly Husz\u00e1r]]. He took part in the consolidation policy of [[Istv\u00e1n Bethlen]] in 1921: as the leader of the main opposition party (the [[Hungarian Social Democratic Party]]) he compromised with the Prime Minister (the Bethlen-Peyer Pact). Peyer was called \"betrayer of the left-wing\" by the [[communist]]s.\n\nIn 1947 Peyer was excluded from his party, so he joined to the Hungarian Radical Party, which organised against communist rule. Soon Peyer emigrated to the [[United States]]. The next year the People's Tribunal sentenced him to 8 years.\n\nPeyer died of a heart attack on 25 October 1956, while listening to the news of the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]], which broke out two days earlier.\n\n==References==\n* [http://mek.oszk.hu/00300/00355/html/index.html Magyar \u00c9letrajzi Lexikon]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Interior Minister of Hungary|Minister of the Interior]]|before=[[Jen\u0151 Landler]] and [[B\u00e9la V\u00e1g\u00f3]]|after=[[Adolf Samassa]]|years=1919}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{HungarianInteriorMinisters}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peyer, Karoly}}\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1956 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Veszpr\u00e9m County]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Social Democratic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Radical Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Interior Ministers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Diet of Hungary]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of Hungary (1945\u20131947)]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of Hungary (1947\u20131949)]]\n[[Category:Hungarian emigrants to the United States]]\n\n\n{{Hungary-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Gladynova", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K%C3%A1roly_Peyer"}
